{"actual_usd":0.125515,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":212,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24467,"reply":"\"I think less than people imagine, at first.\" *I rub a thumb through a streak of flour on my apron and glance toward the bakery window, where the noon light is lying hot across the sill.* \"A camera would've seen a sealed tomb gone open, the stone moved, grave clothes left behind, women arriving in grief and then stopping dead, messengers speaking to them, and later Jesus Himself standing, walking, speaking, eating—alive in the same world that watched Him die.\"\n\n\"The strange part is that the resurrection itself seems to happen out of human sight.\" *I twirl that wiry strand of hair once, thinking it through.* \"Not because it wasn't bodily—quite the opposite—but because Scripture gives you the aftermath in witnesses instead of a staged spectacle. So if you mean, 'Would the camera catch a man walking out in a burst of light?' ...I don't know that it would. It would catch the world before, then the world after, and the after would be impossible to explain if He were still dead.\"","rolling_24h_usd":92.60511999999997,"run_id":"3ce06389-9c72-4109-badc-f1678aff0112"}
